                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/01/2003&nbsp;: 11:09:17 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> I don't have DMF, and don't have necro friends willing to run to me and give it. Extended range items drop from mobs much higher than me, and are sold for much more than I have. (Still hovering at 50pp... come on Torvonillous players... help a brotha out =P I know you got oodles of plat sitting around not being used at all) <br /><br />By the way, would anyone happen to know what level the HG's in Rathe or NK etc. would be soloable for an untwinked necro? I'm sure there are other posts around with the answer, but i'm already typing here =P</span></font></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Zerp</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/01/2003&nbsp;: 11:04:57 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> As mentioned above, to run faster the easiest option is to buy sow potions. <br />Something that was not mentioned is the use of DMF. If you are hunting over hilly areas, DMF can often help you gain distance from your target. You levitate, mobs walk up and down hill thus making their path longer. With a bit of inventiveness, it can be used in many spots to your advantage.<br />Items with extended range help as well. Often times, it will be hard to resnare a planar mob even if you can outrun it, cause it will cover your spell casting range faster than you can cast dooming darkness... Extended range makes is less of an issue (a Drachnid Thyxl, or however that is spelled, is very easy to get... and cermaic swords are getting cheaper by the day).</span></font></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Quitealmighty</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/01/2003&nbsp;: 10:59:29 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Unfortunately i've realized the reason I go so low on HP and Mana so quickly is because of the lack of twinkage I was able to put on my poor little necro. I experimented all day with different ways of killing, and i've found my niche in the ping-pong with the level 4 fear, darkness, leach, med. Thanks again =)</span></font></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Kaldien</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/01/2003&nbsp;: 8:05:59 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> When fear kiting (best solo tactic until around 51, then planes group become more viable), you should always be full mana.  In fact, I was usually full mana and (not realizing it) draining my health down when fear kiting.  Why, because when you Snare it, Fear it, Lifetap DoT it, and Boil Blood it, it cares less what pet it beating on it.  It wants YOU.  So when fear breaks, the mob will come back and you can just refear and sit back down.  I've died lots of times to the level 49 Lich not being used to the high HP demand it has.  After you get used to it, you rule.<br /><br />In PoP groups at about low 50s, I would usually give the Cleric half my mana when she is below 70% mana to fill her up because after we were done I was still full health and mana due to Bond of Death and Lich.  I also had Zlandicar's Heart and with a Shaman in the group with Regrowth, I barely lost any health with Lich on.  I would just wait for the pull, let tank get agro, sic in pet, Slow (if undead), Degeneration, Bond of Death (Always got summoned here, just ran awan and let BoD heal me up), and then wait for it to die.  Maybe throw a nuke now and then if it was undead mob.  Lich spells are a trademark Necromancer spell line.  Without them, you pretty much downgrade to being the weakest caster with the most mana inefficient spells.</span></font></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Aeriform</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/01/2003&nbsp;: 4:18:47 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Your options are:<br />-run farther before you cast<br />-cast a lower level lifetap with a faster cast time<br />-fight mobs that run more slowly (mobs at the same level may run at different speeds)<br />-back off pet, root, lifetap/med until root breaks, sick pet on mob/continue aggro kiting<br />-pull with a lifetap dot, leach I guess or what ever you have atm, finish with a lifetap dot if the mob is running away<br />-ping-pong kite by using level 4 fear, fear breaks and mob comes back to you, re-fear. Fear shouldn't last too long on some mobs, so they should still be in with-in sight. Also creates some good aggro as wel.<br /><br />Ensure you get invoke fear. It is the best fear spell we get (for fear kiting). Many high level necro's will do the combine for you if you give them the components and happen to be in the same zone.</span></font></td>
              </tr>
